    <h3 class="text-center">The Nine Key Physical Aspects on Tai Chi Posture</h3>
    <h3 class="text-center">(太極拳姿勢身法之九大要項)</h3>
    <hr>
    <br><br>

    <p>
        (A) Head, Neck, and Eyes<br>
    <ol>
        <li> 虛領頂勁: The head and the neck are to be vertically aligned</li>
        <li> 兩眼平視: Both eyes are to be level, yet constantly following hte current action</li>
    </ol>
    </p>
    <br>
    <p>
        (B) Upper Torso, Shoulders, and Upper Limbs<br>
    <ol>
        <li> 含胸技背: The chest is to be curved slightly inwards, while hte back is arched slightly outwards</li>
        <li> 沈肩墜肘: Shoulders are to be relaxed, while both elbows are to be dropped</li>
    </ol>
    </p>

    <br>
    <p>
        (C) Forearms, Wrists, and Hands<br>
    <ol>
        <li> 轉腕旋脖: All outward arm movements are to be initiated by circular motions of the wrists and the forearms</li>
        <li> 展指凸掌: Similarly, all such movements are to performed with fingers spread and palms forwardly projected</li>
    </ol>
    </p>

    <br>
    <p>
        (D) Lower Torso and Lower Limbs<br>
    <ol>
        <li> 弓腰收臀: The lower back is to remain relaxed that the pelvis will not be tilted out backwards</li>
        <li> 屈膝坐腿: When bending knees, the upper body appear to lower down vertically, instead of tilting forwards or backwards</li>
        <li> 尾間中正: The coccyx (and therefore, the secrum) is to be aligned vertically.</li>
    </ol>
    </p>
